The regulations shall require the freestanding medical facility to:
Be open 24 hours a day, 7 days a week;
Have available at all times:
At least 1 physician who is credentialed in emergency medicine by the hospital of which the freestanding medical facility is an administrative part;
A sufficient number of registered nurses and other health care professionals to provide advanced life support;
Basic diagnostic and laboratory facilities and technicians;
Resuscitation supplies and equipment, including monitors, defibrillators, cardiac medications, intubation equipment, and intravenous line equipment;
A commercial ambulance for transport of individuals in need of hospitalization or other emergency care; and
Emergency services to all individuals, regardless of ability to pay;
Comply with all Maryland Institute for Emergency Medical Services Systems emergency transport protocols established for the freestanding medical facility;
Comply, except in a life-threatening emergency in which compliance is not feasible or practicable, with the federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention guidelines on universal precautions; and
Display the notice developed under § 1-207 of the Health Occupations Article that explains the federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention's guidelines on universal precautions at the entrance to the freestanding medical facility;
Refrain from use of the words "emergency department", "emergency room", or "hospital"; and
Meet any other standard that the Secretary deems necessary to ensure the quality and safety of services provided by a freestanding medical facility.
